epth case studies of five exemplary memorial museums that commemorate a range of violent pasts and allow for a chronological and global examination of the trend: the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, DC; the House of Terror in Budapest, Hungary; the Kigali Genocide Memorial Centre in Rwanda; the Museum of Memory and Human Rights in Santiago, Chile; and the National September 11 Memorial Museum in New York. Together, these case studies illustrate the historical emergence and global spread of the memorial museum and show how this new cultural form of commemoration is intended to be used in contemporary societies around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCollective memory. 0aCrimes against humanityxMuseums. 0aGenocidexMuseums. 0aHistorical museums. 0aMemorializationxMuseums. 0aPolitical atrocitiesxMuseums. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  a911 memorial.  a911.  agenocide.  aholocaust museum.  aholocaust.  amemorial museum.  amuseums.  aseptember 11 memorial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813592176zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813592176zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813592176.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3 Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA